<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910729-0140</DOCNO><DOCID>910729-0140.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Campbell Soup Says   Harper Has Resigned   As Its Financial Chief</HL><DATE>07/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   CPB WNEWS</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)</NS><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   CAMDEN, N.J. -- Campbell Soup Co. said Edwin L. Harperresigned as executive vice president and chief financialofficer.   The 49-year-old Mr. Harper, in a company statement, saidhe was leaving at a good time for the company, as Campbellhad completed a turnaround. His resignation was effectivelast Friday, the closing of Campbell's fiscal year.</LP><TEXT>   Nevertheless, he said, &quot;When I joined Campbell in 1986, Ijoined with the hope of someday becoming the CEO. In fact, Iwouldn't have taken the job unless that was a realpossibility.&quot; He added, &quot;It is still my plan to be CEO for amajor corporation and I feel that the last business day of avery successful turnaround year is the time to begin theprocess.&quot;   Campbell said it is conducting an external search for apermanent successor and that Mr. Harper will be replaced inthe interim by a &quot;financial council&quot; that will reportdirectly to David W. Johnson, Campbell's chief executiveofficer.   Mr. Harper said he is talking to a number of companies andis particularly interested in a major firm &quot;that has realchallenges.&quot; He added, &quot;I want to feel I can make a strongpositive contribution.&quot;   Early last year, Mr. Harper served as interim co-chiefexecutive while Campbell decided on a successor to R. GordonMcGovern, who had resigned. Mr. Harper was considered astrong inside candidate for the position, but eventually lostout to Mr. Johnson.</TEXT></DOC>